definition.value: A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine zwitterion in which the two acyl groups contain 42 carbons in total with 7 double bonds.

A reagent that lightens or whitens a substrate through chemical reaction. Bleaching reactions usually involve oxidative or reductive processes that degrade colour systems. Bleaching can occur by destroying one or more of the double bonds in the conjugated chain, by cleaving the conjugated chain, or by oxidation of one of the other moieties in the conjugated chain. Their reactivity results in many bleaches having strong bactericidal, disinfecting, and sterilising properties.
A class of lipoproteins with a density between that of low-density and very-low-density lipoproteins. They are formed by the degradatiion of very-low-density lipoproteins.
A dicarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of at least one of the carboxy groups of ethylmalonic acid.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion resulting from the removal of a proton from both of the carboxylic acid groups of ethylmalonic acid.
A dicarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of at least one of the carboxy groups of 2-hydroxyglutaric acid.
An octadecenoate in which the double bond is at C-9.
A pyridinemonocarboxylate obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any pyridoxic acid.
A dicarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of at least one of the carboxy groups of oxalic acid.
A dicarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of at least one of the carboxy groups of suberic acid.
A dicarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of at least one of the carboxy groups of sebacic acid.
A dicarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of at least one of the carboxy groups of 3-methylsuccinic acid.
An N-acylglycinate obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of hippuric acid (N-benzoylglycine) and its derivatives.
A primary ammonium ion obtained by protonation of the amino group of 5-aminolevulinic acid.
A peptide cation obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group and protonation of the amino and guanidino groups of bradykinin; major species at pH 7.3.
A drug that makes increases the sensitivity of tumour cells to radiation therapy.
A zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the 2-hydroxy group to the adjacent tertiary amino group of oxytetracycline; major species at pH 7.3.
Any organic heteroolycyclic compound whose skeleton two ortho-fused chromene rings, and their derivatives.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion that results from the removal of a proton from both of the carboxylic acid groups of any 3-hydroxydicarboxylic acid.
A carboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups of any dicarboxylic acid that contains no carbon-carbon double bonds.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups of any oxo dicarboxylic acid.
An L-alpha-amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of L-lysine; major species at pH 7.3.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of N-hexanoylglycine, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An organic anion that is the major structure of chlortetracycline at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
Any form of carbon black which has a particle size of less than 100 nm in each dimension.
An alpha-amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of 1-methylhistidine; major species at pH 7.3.
An alpha-amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of 3-methylhistidine; major species at pH 7.3.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of N-isobutyrylglycine, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An acylcholine obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of hexadecanoic acid with the hydroxy group of choline.
A  hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion which is obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of homovanillic acid.
A tricarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of at least one of the carboxy groups of citric acid.
A polyunsaturated fatty acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of either alpha- or gamma-linolenic acid.
A HODE(1-) that is the conjugate base of 9-HODE, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.

A monocarboxylic acid amide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of (2-nitroimidazol-1-yl)acetic acid with the aromatic amino group of benzylamine. Used for treatment of Chagas disease.
Abbreviation for nicotinamide-adenine dinucleotide when its oxidation state is unknown or unspecified. It is used in metabolic pathways like glycolysis and citric acid cycle.
A coenzyme that may be NAD(+) or NADP(+).
A coenzyme that may be NADH or NADPH.
A 3-oxo Delta(1)-steroid that is androst-1-ene substituted by oxo groups at positions 3 and 17.
An iminium betaine obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate group of any N-retinylidene-N-retinylphosphatidylethanolamine.
Any polyunsaturated fatty acid anion carrying one or more hydroperoxy substituents.
A N-(long-chain-acyl)ethanolamine in which the acyl group contains 20 carbons and 4 double bonds.
Any organic compound having an initial boiling point less than or equal to 250 degreeC (482 degreeF) measured at a standard atmospheric pressure of 101.3 kPa.
A phosphatidic acid in which the two acyl groups contain a total of 36 carbons and 2 double bonds.
A phosphatidylethanolamine in which the two acyl groups contain a total of 38 carbons and 5 double bonds.
A phosphatidylethanolamine in which the two acyl groups contain a total of 40 carbons and 6 double bonds.
A phosphatidylethanolamine in which the two acyl groups contain a total of 40 carbons and 5 double bonds.
An alkanesulfonate in which the carbon at position 1 is attached to R, which can represent hydrogens, a carbon chain, or other groups.
Any phenol carrying an additional methoxy substituent at the ortho-position.
